P(slug="nightlife-guide-gurugram", date="2026-02-25", cat="City Guide", city="Gurugram",
  title="Gurugram nightlife: where Delhi-NCR really goes to party",
  excerpt="Cyber Hub, high-rise clubs and big-room energy — a guide to the satellite city that hosts the capital's biggest nights.",
  tags=["Gurugram","Delhi","clubs","travel"],
  body="""<p>Ask where the serious clubbing in the Delhi region actually happens, and the answer increasingly isn't Delhi at all — it's Gurugram. The satellite city's high-rise venues and buzzing hubs have made it the beating heart of NCR nightlife.</p>
<h2>The hubs</h2>
<p>Cyber Hub and the surrounding corporate-and-leisure districts pack in a dense cluster of clubs, gastropubs and rooftop lounges, fuelled by the city's young, high-earning professional crowd. The programming leans big — commercial, Bollywood and big-room electronic nights that pull large weekend crowds and touring names.</p>
<h2>The character</h2>
<p>Gurugram parties with ambition and spending power. Premium venues, strict dress codes and table culture define the top end, while the gastropub scene keeps things accessible for a casual night. It's polished, high-energy and unabashedly about a good time.</p>
<h2>Tips</h2>
<ul><li>Weekends are the main event; book tables ahead at the marquee clubs.</li><li>Dress sharp — the premium venues enforce codes.</li><li>Stay within a hub; the city is spread out and sprawling.</li></ul>
<p>For big-room NCR energy, Gurugram is where the capital region goes large.</p>""")

P(slug="goa-north-vs-south-nightlife", date="2026-01-11", cat="City Guide", city="Goa",
  title="North Goa vs South Goa: which side is your kind of night?",
  excerpt="Two totally different Goas share one coastline. A guide to picking the right side for the night you want.",
  tags=["Goa","beach","travel","guide"],
  body="""<p>People say "Goa" like it's one place, but the party experience up north and down south couldn't be more different. Picking the right side is the difference between the trip you wanted and the trip you didn't.</p>
<h2>North Goa: the engine</h2>
<p>Anjuna, Vagator, Morjim, Ashwem — this is the party heartland. Beach clubs, cliffside sundowners, the big clubs, the touring DJs, the sunrise culture. It's busier, louder and more social, and it's where the vast majority of Goa's nightlife lives. If you came to party, you came for North Goa.</p>
<h2>South Goa: the escape</h2>
<p>The south is quieter, more luxurious and more laid-back — pristine beaches, boutique resorts, and a slower rhythm. There's music and there are sundowners, but the emphasis is on relaxation, not raving. It's where you go to recover, or to do a more refined kind of holiday.</p>
<h2>How to choose</h2>
<ul><li>Want the full party circuit and nightlife? Base yourself in the north.</li><li>Want calm, luxury and space? Head south.</li><li>Doing both? Party north, then decompress south — the classic combo.</li></ul>
<p>Know which Goa you're chasing, and the coast delivers.</p>""")

P(slug="biggest-nye-parties-india", date="2026-07-02", cat="Festival", city="India",
  title="India's biggest New Year's Eve parties: a city-by-city guide",
  excerpt="Goa beaches to Rajasthan lakes to metro rooftops — where the country throws its biggest NYE celebrations.",
  tags=["NYE","festival","guide","India"],
  body="""<p>New Year's Eve is the single biggest night on India's calendar, and every city goes all out. Here's a guide to where the country celebrates hardest — so you can plan the one that suits you (and yes, planning in July is smart).</p>
<h2>Goa: the pilgrimage</h2>
<p>Goa is the default NYE destination, with beach parties, big festival stages and sunrise sessions drawing a national migration. Expect huge crowds, the biggest line-ups and a full week of celebration around the 31st.</p>
<h2>The metros: rooftops and big rooms</h2>
<p>Mumbai, Delhi-NCR, Bengaluru and Hyderabad throw glossy, high-production NYE parties — rooftop countdowns, premium clubs and marquee-venue events with headline DJs.</p>
<h2>Rajasthan: heritage and lakes</h2>
<p>For something more scenic, Udaipur and Jaipur offer palace and lakeside celebrations that trade sheer scale for atmosphere and romance. Our own lakeside NYE flagship at The Udaisarovar sells out every year on the guest list before it's public.</p>
<h2>The rule</h2>
<p>Whatever you choose, book early. NYE is the one night where leaving it late means paying triple — or missing out entirely. Decide your city now, lock your group, and get on the lists.</p>""")

P(slug="nu-disco-funk-revival-india", date="2026-03-05", cat="Genre", city="India",
  title="Nu-disco and funk: the feel-good revival on India's floors",
  excerpt="Groovy, warm and impossible to stand still to — why disco-flavoured house is winning Indian dancefloors.",
  tags=["nu-disco","funk","house","guide"],
  body="""<p>Amid all the techno and afro house, a warmer, funkier sound has been quietly winning hearts on India's floors: nu-disco and its disco-house cousins. If you like your dance music groovy, melodic and pure good-time energy, this is your lane.</p>
<h2>The sound</h2>
<p>Nu-disco takes the funk, soul and disco of decades past — the basslines, the strings, the four-on-the-floor joy — and reworks it with modern production. It's upbeat without being aggressive, sophisticated without being cold, and just about the most instantly danceable music there is.</p>
<h2>Why it fits India</h2>
<p>Indian crowds love melody and a feel-good vibe, and nu-disco delivers both in spades. It works everywhere — a sundowner, a rooftop, a pool party, an early club set — bridging the gap between accessible and credible. It's the sound of a smile on the dancefloor.</p>
<h2>Where to catch it</h2>
<p>Look for it at sundowners and house-leaning nights, and in the sets of DJs who value groove over intensity. In a scene that sometimes takes itself very seriously, nu-disco is a joyful reminder that dance music is, first of all, supposed to be fun.</p>""")

P(slug="resident-dj-role", date="2026-03-13", cat="Scene Report", city="India",
  title="The unsung hero of the club: the resident DJ",
  excerpt="Headliners get the posters, but residents build the sound of a venue. An appreciation of the DJ who plays every week.",
  tags=["culture","DJ","resident"],
  body="""<p>The touring headliner gets the poster and the fee, but the person who actually defines a venue's sound is often the one nobody travels to see: the resident DJ. Residents are the unsung backbone of club culture, and the best of them are masters of a craft the spotlight overlooks.</p>
<h2>What a resident does</h2>
<p>A resident plays their venue regularly — warming up the room, reading the crowd night after night, and shaping the musical identity of the place over months and years. They don't get to parachute in and play only the peak-time bangers; they have to build the night, hold the energy through the quiet hours, and set the stage for whoever headlines.</p>
<h2>The craft</h2>
<p>Warming up well is one of the hardest skills in DJing — filling a room with the right energy without peaking too soon takes deep taste and restraint. Residents master it, and in doing so they learn to truly read a crowd, which is why so many great headliners started as residents.</p>
<h2>The respect</h2>
<p>Next time you're out early and the floor's just filling, pay attention to the resident. They're doing the quiet, skilled work that makes the whole night possible — and they're often the real soul of the venue.</p>""")

P(slug="how-to-find-events-your-city", date="2026-05-09", cat="Playbook", city="India",
  title="How to actually find the best events in your city",
  excerpt="Stop missing the good nights. A practical guide to discovering the parties worth your time.",
  tags=["guide","tips","discovery"],
  body="""<p>The best nights in any city often fly under the radar — sold out on a guest list before you even heard about them. Here's how to plug into the scene so you stop finding out about the great parties the day after.</p>
<h2>Follow the promoters, not just the venues</h2>
<p>Venues host all kinds of nights of wildly varying quality; the collective or promoter is what determines whether a party is actually good. Find the crews whose taste matches yours and follow them directly. Their social feeds are where the real calendar lives.</p>
<h2>Get on the guest lists</h2>
<p>The best events open their guest lists — usually on WhatsApp or Instagram — before public tickets. Joining them is how you hear first and pay least. (Ours is a message away at +91 91160 20099.)</p>
<h2>Use the tools, then go deeper</h2>
<ul><li>Ticketing platforms and event apps are good for the big, mainstream shows.</li><li>Instagram's local tags and story reshares surface the smaller underground nights.</li><li>Word of mouth still rules — the best recommendations come from friends already in the scene.</li></ul>
<h2>The habit</h2>
<p>Curate your feed toward the promoters and artists you love, join the lists, and the good nights will start coming to you. That's how the people who never seem to miss a great party do it.</p>""")

P(slug="july-nightlife-metros-2026", date="2026-07-06", cat="Upcoming", city="India",
  title="July nights: what's on across India's metros this monsoon",
  excerpt="Mumbai to Bengaluru to Delhi — a city-by-city look at where to be on a rainy July weekend.",
  tags=["July","2026","monsoon","metros"],
  body="""<p>Monsoon or not, India's big cities keep the weekend alive through July — you just have to know where to look. Here's a city-by-city read on the indoor season at its peak.</p>
<h2>Mumbai</h2>
<p>The country's deepest club calendar barely blinks at the rain. Lower Parel and Bandra keep the weekends stacked with touring selectors and resident nights, and the covered rooftops turn the monsoon skyline into a feature. Mumbai is the safest bet for a guaranteed great July night.</p>
<h2>Bengaluru</h2>
<p>The underground and microbrewery scenes are made for this weather — intimate rooms, craft beer, live music and house-and-techno nights for the city's famously discerning crowd. Monsoon Bengaluru is cosy and consistently excellent.</p>
<h2>Delhi-NCR</h2>
<p>The big indoor venues in Gurugram and central Delhi carry the season with commercial and electronic programming. Pick a covered venue and the rain won't touch your night.</p>
<h2>The rest</h2>
<p>Hyderabad and Pune keep their weekend rooms busy, and Goa offers its moody, uncrowded off-season for the adventurous. Wherever you are, July rewards the crowd that shows up rain or shine — and that crowd always has the better night.</p>""")

P(slug="udaipur-christmas-festival-recap", date="2026-01-04", cat="Pronite Recap", city="Udaipur",
  title="Udaipur Christmas Festival: how the city celebrated the season",
  excerpt="A festive-season celebration that brought the whole city together — a look back at the Udaipur Christmas Festival.",
  tags=["Christmas","festival","Udaipur","recap"],
  body="""<p>Christmas in Udaipur has a warmth all its own, and the Udaipur Christmas Festival leaned right into it — a festive-season celebration that turned the holiday weekend into one of the city's most joyful gatherings.</p>
<h2>The festive spirit</h2>
<p>Christmas week sits right at the start of India's biggest party stretch, running straight into the New Year's rush, and the crowd comes out in full holiday mood. The festival matched that energy with a celebratory, all-ages spirit — music, festivity and the particular magic of the season in a city as beautiful as Udaipur.</p>
<h2>Why the season matters</h2>
<p>The Christmas-to-New-Year window is the busiest and most special on our calendar. It's when the city fills with visitors, the weather is perfect, and everyone's in the mood to celebrate. Events like this set the tone for the countdown to midnight on the 31st.</p>
<h2>The tradition continues</h2>
<p>Each year the festive season gives us a chance to bring the city together before the New Year's flagship. If a Udaipur Christmas is on your list, plan ahead — the whole season books out fast, and the guest list is the way in.</p>""")

P(slug="sound-system-culture-india", date="2026-06-15", cat="Scene Report", city="India",
  title="Why the sound system makes or breaks the night",
  excerpt="The most underrated part of any party isn't the DJ — it's the rig. An appreciation of sound-system culture.",
  tags=["culture","sound","India"],
  body="""<p>Here's something casual party-goers rarely think about but every serious head obsesses over: the sound system. You can have the best DJ in the world, but on a bad rig the night falls flat. Sound-system culture is one of the quiet foundations of a great scene.</p>
<h2>Why it matters so much</h2>
<p>Dance music is physical — it's meant to be felt in the chest and the floor, not just heard. A properly designed, well-tuned sound system delivers clean, powerful low-end and clear detail across the whole frequency range, so a two-hour set stays exciting instead of turning into muddy noise. It's the difference between hearing a track and being inside it.</p>
<h2>The connoisseur's obsession</h2>
<p>Globally, entire party cultures are built around legendary sound systems, and India's underground increasingly values the same thing. Promoters who invest in a great rig are rewarded with crowds who can feel the difference, even if they can't name it.</p>
<h2>The Pronite view</h2>
<p>It's why we treat sound as non-negotiable at our events — outdoor techno by the lake only works if the system can carry it. Next time a night feels transcendent, know that the rig did a lot of the quiet work. Great sound is invisible when it's right, and impossible to ignore when it's wrong.</p>""")

P(slug="afterparty-culture-india", date="2026-06-21", cat="Scene Report", city="India",
  title="The afterparty: where the night's best stories are made",
  excerpt="When the club closes, the real night begins. An ode to afterparty culture and the people who never go home.",
  tags=["culture","afterparty","India"],
  body="""<p>Every scene has its worst-kept secret: the afterparty. When the main venue shuts and most of the crowd heads home, a dedicated few carry the night onward — and more often than not, that's where the best stories are made.</p>
<h2>Why the afterparty is special</h2>
<p>By the time a night rolls into its afterparty, the crowd has distilled to the true believers. The pretence is gone, the vibe is looser and more intimate, and the music often goes deeper and weirder than a main-room set ever could. It's the antidote to the polished, ticketed club night — spontaneous, communal and unrepeatable.</p>
<h2>The India context</h2>
<p>From Goa's legendary into-the-daylight sessions to the low-key gatherings that follow a great city club night, afterparty culture is woven through Indian nightlife. It's where friendships form, where the deepest sets happen, and where the sunrise crowd earns its stripes.</p>
<h2>A word of care</h2>
<p>The afterparty is magic, but it's also where pacing matters most — the people still standing at noon are the ones who looked after themselves. Enjoy it, look out for each other, and know when to call it. The best afterparties are the ones everyone remembers fondly.</p>""")
